{
  "doc_id": "40338",
  "text": "Simple anthropometric measures, such as body mass index (BMI) and waist circumference, have been used to investigate the association between adiposity and cardiovascular risk factors in adults [CITATION_1] . Recently, studies on children seem to confirm the usefulness of waist circumference as an appropriate index of metabolic and cardiovascular risk also in the pre-puberty years [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . However, few data are available for the period during puberty. Puberty affects cardiovascular and metabolic risk factors differently in males and females by the combined effects of hormones, changes of body composition and body fat distribution, and psycho-behavioural changes that may have relevant effects on one's lifestyle and nutritional habits.",
